<button class="accordion">What are factors to consider in any manual handling activity?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>For any lifting activity, it is vital to consider the following factors:</p>
<li> Individual capability</li>
<li> The nature of the load</li>
<li> Environmental conditions</li>
<li> Training</li>
<li> Work organisation.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Which legislation relates to manual handling?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Health and Safety at Work etc Act 1974 (HSWA) is the cornerstone of safe working practices, healthy environments and avoidance of accidents in the workplace, and has sections relevant to manual handling. Management of Health and Safety at Work Regulations 1999 reinforces the 1974 act.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is Manual Handling Operations Regulations 2002?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The Manual Handling Operations Regulations (MHOR) is a piece of health and safety legislation that affects both employers and employees. It passed into law in 1992 and was amended in 2002.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">How can I ensure that my business is compliant with the Manual Handling Operations Regulations?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>It is essential to be mindful of the following:</p>
<li> Follow the guidance contained within the regulations.</li>
<li> Ensure that you have up-to-date and concise risk assessment plans in place for all the manual handling tasks that your employees undertake.</li>
<li> Ensure providing adequate and frequent training and refresher training for your employees.</li>
<li> If you have manual handling instructors, you must ensure meeting your instructor training and refresher commitments.</li>
